Netflix Rating Prediction Project

This notebook implements a machine learning model to predict Netflix content ratings based on text descriptions and metadata.

5. Test Predictions

In[23]:
def predict_example(description, content_type='Movie', release_year=2022):
    """Make a prediction for an example content description"""
    # Clean text
    clean_desc = clean_text(description)
    
    # Create features
    features = {
        'type_encoded': 1 if content_type == 'TV Show' else 0,
        'release_year': release_year,
        'description_length': len(description),
        'title_length': 0,  # Not relevant for prediction
        'token_count': len(tokenize_text(clean_desc)),
        'sentiment_polarity': analyze_sentiment(description)['polarity'],
        'sentiment_subjectivity': analyze_sentiment(description)['subjectivity']
    }
    
    # Add genre features (all 0 for simplicity)
    for col in X.columns:
        if col.startswith('genre_') and col not in features:
            features[col] = 0
    
    # Create DataFrame
    features_df = pd.DataFrame([features])
    
    # Ensure columns match training data
    missing_cols = set(X.columns) - set(features_df.columns)
    for col in missing_cols:
        features_df[col] = 0
    features_df = features_df[X.columns]
    
    # Make prediction
    result = model.predict_rating(features_df)
    return result

Text Mining Enhancements

In[34]:
# Part-of-Speech Analysis
from collections import Counter
import nltk
nltk.download('averaged_perceptron_tagger')

# Sample some descriptions
sample_descriptions = processor.df['clean_description'].sample(100)

# Extract and analyze POS tags
def analyze_pos(text):
    tokens = tokenize_text(text, remove_stopwords=False)
    tagged = nltk.pos_tag(tokens)
    return Counter(tag for word, tag in tagged)

pos_distributions = sample_descriptions.apply(analyze_pos)
pos_counts = sum(pos_distributions, Counter())

# Plot POS distribution
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
common_pos = dict(pos_counts.most_common(10))
sns.barplot(x=list(common_pos.keys()), y=list(common_pos.values()))
plt.title('Most Common Parts of Speech in Netflix Descriptions')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Topic Modeling

In[37]:
# LDA Topic Modeling
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer

# Create a document-term matrix
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(max_df=0.95, min_df=2, stop_words='english')
dtm = vectorizer.fit_transform(processor.df['clean_description'])

# Create and fit LDA model
lda = LatentDirichletAllocation(n_components=5, random_state=42)
lda.fit(dtm)

# Print top words in each topic
feature_names = vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()
for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(lda.components_):
    print(f"Topic #{topic_idx + 1}:")
    top_words = [feature_names[i] for i in topic.argsort()[:-11:-1]]
    print(", ".join(top_words))
    print()

# Assign topics to documents
topic_results = lda.transform(dtm)
processor.df['dominant_topic'] = topic_results.argmax(axis=1)

# Compare ratings across topics
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.countplot(x='dominant_topic', hue='rating', data=processor.df)
plt.title('Rating Distribution Across Topics')
plt.xlabel('Topic')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.show()

In[40]:
# Word Embeddings with Gensim Word2Vec
from gensim.models import Word2Vec

# Prepare corpus
sentences = processor.df['clean_description'].apply(tokenize_text).tolist()

# Train Word2Vec model
word2vec_model = Word2Vec(sentences=sentences, vector_size=100, window=5, min_count=5, workers=4)
word2vec_model.save("netflix_word2vec.model")

# Find similar words
print("Words similar to 'family':")
similar_words = word2vec_model.wv.most_similar('family', topn=10)
for word, similarity in similar_words:
    print(f"{word}: {similarity:.4f}")

# Create document vectors
def get_doc_vector(tokens, model):
    # Filter out words not in vocabulary
    tokens = [word for word in tokens if word in model.wv.key_to_index]
    if not tokens:
        return np.zeros(model.vector_size)
    return np.mean([model.wv[word] for word in tokens], axis=0)

# Add document vectors to features
doc_vectors = processor.df['clean_description'].apply(tokenize_text).apply(lambda x: get_doc_vector(x, word2vec_model))
doc_vector_array = np.vstack(doc_vectors.values)

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.naive_bayes import MultinomialNB
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score


# Prepare data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y)

# Dictionary to store results
results = {}

# Random Forest (already implemented)
results['Random Forest'] = model.model

# Logistic Regression
lr = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, C=1.0, random_state=42)
lr.fit(X_train, y_train)
lr_pred = lr.predict(X_test)
results['Logistic Regression'] = lr

# Naive Bayes (for text classification)
# Convert to non-negative values for Multinomial NB
X_train_nb = X_train.clip(lower=0)
X_test_nb = X_test.clip(lower=0)
nb = MultinomialNB()
nb.fit(X_train_nb, y_train)
nb_pred = nb.predict(X_test_nb)
results['Naive Bayes'] = nb

# Compare accuracies
accuracies = {
    'Random Forest': accuracy_score(y_test, model.model.predict(X_test)),
    'Logistic Regression': accuracy_score(y_test, lr_pred),
    'Naive Bayes': accuracy_score(y_test, nb_pred)
}

# Plot comparison
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x=list(accuracies.keys()), y=list(accuracies.values()))
plt.title('Model Accuracy Comparison')
plt.ylim(0, 1)
plt.show()

Project Summary and Analysis

Netflix Rating Prediction: Text Analytics Project Summary

Key Findings

  1. Model Performance: The Random Forest model achieved 46.47% accuracy on the test set.

  2. Important Features: The most predictive features are:

    • Release year
    • Title length
    • Sentiment polarity and subjectivity
    • Description length

  3. Topic Analysis:

    • Topic 1: Entertainment/Drama (world, love, friends, comedy)
    • Topic 2: Documentaries (documentary, series, film, lives)
    • Topic 3: Coming-of-age (young, school, woman, friends)
    • Topic 4: Family (family, young, old, home)
    • Topic 5: Character-driven (man, family, father, woman)

  4. Prediction Patterns:

    • The model tends to predict TV-MA most frequently
    • Sentiment characteristics vary significantly between content ratings
    • Model struggles most with the "Other" category

Applied Text Analytics Techniques

  • Tokenization and text cleaning
  • Part-of-speech tagging
  • Topic modeling with LDA
  • Word embeddings with Word2Vec
  • Sentiment analysis

# Add all required imports
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline, FeatureUnion
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
import numpy as np

# Create TF-IDF features
tfidf = TfidfVectorizer(max_features=1000, min_df=5, max_df=0.85)
text_features = tfidf.fit_transform(processor.df['clean_description'])

# Combine with existing features
X_combined = np.hstack((X.values, text_features.toarray()))

# Train an enhanced model
X_train_combined, X_test_combined, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_combined, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y)

enhanced_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, max_depth=20, random_state=42)
enhanced_model.fit(X_train_combined, y_train)
enhanced_pred = enhanced_model.predict(X_test_combined)

print(f"Enhanced model accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, enhanced_pred):.4f}")

Final Insights

Conclusions and Applications

  1. Rating Predictability: Content ratings can be predicted with moderate accuracy (46.47%) using text descriptions and metadata alone.

  2. Feature Importance: The release year is the most predictive feature, followed by text characteristics like title length and sentiment. This suggests that rating standards have evolved over time.

  3. Text Patterns: Each rating category has distinct linguistic patterns:

    • TV-MA content uses more adult themes and negative sentiment
    • G and TV-Y content shows more positive sentiment and family-oriented terms
    • PG-13 content tends to balance between these extremes

  4. Applications:

    • Content creators can use these insights to tailor descriptions for target audiences
    • Streaming platforms can better categorize and recommend content
    • This approach demonstrates how text analytics can extract meaningful patterns from content descriptions

# Identify under-rated content
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

# Create numerical mapping for ratings (for comparison purposes)
rating_order = {
    'G': 1, 'TV-Y': 1, 'TV-G': 2, 'PG': 3, 'TV-Y7': 3, 
    'TV-PG': 4, 'PG-13': 5, 'TV-14': 6, 'R': 7, 'TV-MA': 7, 'Other': 8
}

# Add numerical values to dataset
processor.df['rating_value'] = processor.df['rating'].map(rating_order)

# Make predictions on the entire dataset
all_features = X.copy()
all_predictions = model.model.predict(all_features)

# Convert categorical predictions to numerical
predicted_values = [rating_order[pred] for pred in all_predictions]

# Calculate rating difference (predicted - actual)
processor.df['predicted_rating'] = all_predictions
processor.df['predicted_value'] = predicted_values
processor.df['rating_difference'] = processor.df['predicted_value'] - processor.df['rating_value']

# Identify underrated content (predicted rating higher than actual)
underrated = processor.df[processor.df['rating_difference'] > 1].sort_values('rating_difference', ascending=False)

print(f"Found {len(underrated)} potentially underrated titles")
print("\nTop 10 Most Underrated Titles:")
for i, (_, row) in enumerate(underrated.head(10).iterrows()):
    print(f"{i+1}. {row['title']} ({row['type']}, {row['release_year']})")
    print(f"   Actual: {row['rating']}, Predicted: {row['predicted_rating']}")
    print(f"   Description: {row['description'][:100]}...")

Genre-Adjusted Rating System

In[64]:
# Design a genre-adjusted rating system
import pandas as pd

# Extract all genres
all_genres = []
for genres in processor.df['listed_in'].str.split(','):
    if isinstance(genres, list):
        all_genres.extend([g.strip() for g in genres])

# Get unique genres
unique_genres = list(set(all_genres))

# Calculate average rating value by genre
genre_ratings = {}
for genre in unique_genres:
    # Find all titles with this genre
    titles_with_genre = processor.df[processor.df['listed_in'].str.contains(genre, na=False)]
    if len(titles_with_genre) > 10:  # Only consider genres with sufficient data
        avg_rating = titles_with_genre['rating_value'].mean()
        genre_ratings[genre] = {
            'avg_rating': avg_rating,
            'count': len(titles_with_genre)
        }

# Sort genres by average rating
sorted_genres = sorted(genre_ratings.items(), key=lambda x: x[1]['avg_rating'], reverse=True)

print("Genres by Average Content Rating (highest to lowest):")
for genre, stats in sorted_genres:
    print(f"{genre}: {stats['avg_rating']:.2f} (from {stats['count']} titles)")

# For each title, calculate genre-adjusted rating
def get_genre_adjusted_rating(row):
    if not isinstance(row['listed_in'], str):
        return 0
    
    genres = [g.strip() for g in row['listed_in'].split(',')]
    genre_avgs = [genre_ratings.get(g, {'avg_rating': 0})['avg_rating'] for g in genres]
    if not genre_avgs or sum(genre_avgs) == 0:
        return 0
    
    avg_genre_rating = sum(genre_avgs) / len(genre_avgs)
    return row['rating_value'] - avg_genre_rating

# Calculate adjusted ratings
processor.df['genre_adjusted_rating'] = processor.df.apply(get_genre_adjusted_rating, axis=1)

# Find standout content in each genre (highest adjusted ratings)
print("\nStandout Content By Genre:")
for genre in sorted([g for g in genre_ratings.keys()]):
    titles = processor.df[processor.df['listed_in'].str.contains(genre, na=False)]
    if len(titles) > 0:
        # Get top title by adjusted rating
        top_title = titles.sort_values('genre_adjusted_rating', ascending=False).iloc[0]
        print(f"\n{genre}:")
        print(f"  Top Title: {top_title['title']} ({top_title['type']}, {top_title['release_year']})")
        print(f"  Rating: {top_title['rating']} (Genre avg: {genre_ratings[genre]['avg_rating']:.2f})")

# Predict rating using pre-release metadata
# Select only features available before release
pre_release_features = [
    'type_encoded', 'title_length', 'description_length', 'token_count',
    'sentiment_polarity', 'sentiment_subjectivity'
]

# Add genre features
genre_features = [col for col in X.columns if col.startswith('genre_')]
pre_release_features.extend(genre_features)

# Create pre-release feature set
X_pre_release = X[pre_release_features]

# Train and evaluate a pre-release model
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, classification_report

X_train_pre, X_test_pre, y_train_pre, y_test_pre = train_test_split(
    X_pre_release, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

pre_release_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, max_depth=20, random_state=42)
pre_release_model.fit(X_train_pre, y_train_pre)

# Evaluate pre-release model
pre_release_preds = pre_release_model.predict(X_test_pre)
pre_release_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test_pre, pre_release_preds)

print(f"Pre-release model accuracy: {pre_release_accuracy:.4f}")
print("\nComparison:")
print(f"Full model accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, model.model.predict(X_test)):.4f}")
print(f"Pre-release model accuracy: {pre_release_accuracy:.4f}")
print(f"Difference: {accuracy_score(y_test, model.model.predict(X_test)) - pre_release_accuracy:.4f}")

print("\nFeature importance for pre-release prediction:")
pre_release_importance = pd.DataFrame({
    'Feature': X_pre_release.columns,
    'Importance': pre_release_model.feature_importances_
}).sort_values('Importance', ascending=False)

print(pre_release_importance.head(10))

Predict Rating Range (1-5 Scale)

In[70]:
# Convert ratings to a 1-5 scale
rating_scale = {
    'G': 1, 'TV-Y': 1, 'TV-G': 1.5,
    'PG': 2, 'TV-Y7': 2, 'TV-PG': 2.5,
    'PG-13': 3, 'TV-14': 3.5,
    'R': 4, 'TV-MA': 4.5, 
    'Other': 3  # Default for other ratings
}

# Create numerical target variable
y_numeric = processor.df['rating'].map(rating_scale)

# Train a regression model
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error

X_train_reg, X_test_reg, y_train_reg, y_test_reg = train_test_split(
    X, y_numeric, test_size=0.3, random_state=42
)

reg_model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, max_depth=20, random_state=42)
reg_model.fit(X_train_reg, y_train_reg)

# Make predictions
reg_preds = reg_model.predict(X_test_reg)

# Evaluate regression model
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test_reg, reg_preds)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test_reg, reg_preds)
rmse = mse ** 0.5

print(f"Regression to 1-5 scale:")
print(f"Mean Squared Error: {mse:.4f}")
print(f"Root Mean Squared Error: {rmse:.4f}")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error: {mae:.4f}")

# Visualize predictions vs actual
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(y_test_reg, reg_preds, alpha=0.3)
plt.plot([1, 5], [1, 5], 'r--')
plt.xlabel('Actual Rating')
plt.ylabel('Predicted Rating')
plt.title('Predicted vs Actual Ratings (1-5 Scale)')
plt.xlim(0.5, 5.5)
plt.ylim(0.5, 5.5)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# Detailed error analysis

metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(class_report).transpose()
print("\nClass-specific metrics:")
print(metrics_df)

# Confusion matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
cm_normalized = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]

# Plot normalized confusion matrix
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
sns.heatmap(cm_normalized, annot=True, fmt='.2f', cmap='Blues',
            xticklabels=model.model.classes_,
            yticklabels=model.model.classes_)
plt.xlabel('Predicted')
plt.ylabel('True')
plt.title('Normalized Confusion Matrix')
plt.show()

# Error analysis by feature value
error_analysis = []
for i, (pred, true) in enumerate(zip(y_pred, y_test)):
    if pred != true:
        error_analysis.append({
            'true': true,
            'predicted': pred,
            'release_year': X_test.iloc[i]['release_year'],
            'sentiment_polarity': X_test.iloc[i]['sentiment_polarity'],
            'description_length': X_test.iloc[i]['description_length']
        })

error_df = pd.DataFrame(error_analysis)

# Check error patterns
print("\nError analysis by release year:")
print(error_df.groupby('true')['release_year'].mean())

print("\nError analysis by sentiment:")
print(error_df.groupby('true')['sentiment_polarity'].mean())

# Visualize errors by feature value

plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Advanced Deep Learning Implementation

In[76]:
# Advanced Deep Learning with LSTM
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.text import Tokenizer
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.sequence import pad_sequences
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Embedding, LSTM, Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.utils import to_categorical
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

# Prepare text data
descriptions = processor.df['clean_description'].tolist()
ratings = processor.df['rating'].tolist()

# Encode labels
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
y_encoded = label_encoder.fit_transform(ratings)
y_categorical = to_categorical(y_encoded)

# Tokenize text
max_features = 5000  # Maximum vocabulary size
max_length = 100     # Maximum sequence length

tokenizer = Tokenizer(num_words=max_features)
tokenizer.fit_on_texts(descriptions)
sequences = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(descriptions)
X_padded = pad_sequences(sequences, maxlen=max_length)

# Split data
X_train_dl, X_test_dl, y_train_dl, y_test_dl = train_test_split(
    X_padded, y_categorical, test_size=0.2, random_state=42
)

# Define LSTM model
model_lstm = Sequential()
model_lstm.add(Embedding(max_features, 128, input_length=max_length))
model_lstm.add(LSTM(64, dropout=0.2, recurrent_dropout=0.2))
model_lstm.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
model_lstm.add(Dropout(0.5))
model_lstm.add(Dense(y_categorical.shape[1], activation='softmax'))

# Compile model
model_lstm.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', 
                 optimizer='adam', 
                 metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train model (comment out for quick execution)
history = model_lstm.fit(
    X_train_dl, y_train_dl,
    epochs=5,
    batch_size=32,
    validation_split=0.2,
    verbose=1
)

# Evaluate model
scores = model_lstm.evaluate(X_test_dl, y_test_dl, verbose=0)
print(f"LSTM Model Accuracy: {scores[1]:.4f}")

# Compare with Random Forest
print(f"Random Forest Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
print(f"Improvement with Deep Learning: {scores[1] - accuracy:.4f}")

# Plot training history
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
plt.title('Model Accuracy')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc='upper left')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('Model Loss')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.legend(['Train', 'Validation'], loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Cross-Validation Implementation

In[79]:
# Implement cross-validation for model robustness
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score, StratifiedKFold

# Define cross-validation strategy
cv = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

# Models to evaluate
models = {
    'Random Forest': RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, max_depth=20, random_state=42),
    'Logistic Regression': LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, C=1.0, random_state=42),
    'Naive Bayes': MultinomialNB()
}

# Perform cross-validation
cv_results = {}
for name, model in models.items():
    if name == 'Naive Bayes':
        # Use non-negative values for Naive Bayes
        scores = cross_val_score(model, X.clip(lower=0), y, cv=cv, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1)
    else:
        scores = cross_val_score(model, X, y, cv=cv, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1)
    
    cv_results[name] = {
        'mean_accuracy': scores.mean(),
        'std_accuracy': scores.std(),
        'scores': scores
    }
    print(f"{name}: {scores.mean():.4f} ({scores.std():.4f})")

# Visualize cross-validation results
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
means = [result['mean_accuracy'] for result in cv_results.values()]
stds = [result['std_accuracy'] for result in cv_results.values()]
names = list(cv_results.keys())

plt.bar(names, means, yerr=stds, alpha=0.8, capsize=10)
plt.title('Cross-Validation Results (5-Fold)')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.ylim(0, 1)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
plt.show()

Simple Deployment Example

In[88]:
# Fixed prediction function that works with trained scikit-learn models
def predict_rating_from_description(description, trained_model, content_type='Movie', release_year=2022):
    """
    Predict content rating from a description using a trained scikit-learn model.
    """
    # Import necessary functions
    from text_analytics_utils import clean_text, tokenize_text, analyze_sentiment
    from sklearn.naive_bayes import MultinomialNB
    
    # Clean text
    clean_desc = clean_text(description)
    
    # Create features
    features = {
        'type_encoded': 1 if content_type == 'TV Show' else 0,
        'release_year': release_year,
        'description_length': len(description),
        'title_length': 0,  # Not relevant for prediction
        'token_count': len(tokenize_text(clean_desc)),
        'sentiment_polarity': analyze_sentiment(description)['polarity'],
        'sentiment_subjectivity': analyze_sentiment(description)['subjectivity']
    }
    
    # Add genre features (all 0 for simplicity)
    import pandas as pd
    for col in X.columns:
        if col.startswith('genre_') and col not in features:
            features[col] = 0
    
    # Create DataFrame
    features_df = pd.DataFrame([features])
    
    # Ensure columns match training data
    missing_cols = set(X.columns) - set(features_df.columns)
    for col in missing_cols:
        features_df[col] = 0
    features_df = features_df[X.columns]
    
    # For Naive Bayes, make sure values are non-negative
    if isinstance(trained_model, MultinomialNB):
        features_df = features_df.clip(lower=0)
    
    # Make prediction using standard scikit-learn interface
    predicted_rating = trained_model.predict(features_df)[0]
    
    # Get probabilities
    probabilities = trained_model.predict_proba(features_df)[0]
    
    # Sort probabilities
    top_ratings = [(trained_model.classes_[i], probabilities[i]) 
                   for i in probabilities.argsort()[::-1]]
    
    return {
        'description': description,
        'predicted_rating': predicted_rating,
        'confidence': max(probabilities),
        'top_ratings': top_ratings
    }

# Example usage with a TRAINED model from your results dictionary
test_descriptions = [
    "A heartwarming story about friendship and growing up in a small town.",
    "A brutal examination of violence and revenge in the criminal underworld.",
    "A funny comedy about college students planning the ultimate party.",
    "An exploration of scientific discoveries that changed human history."
]

# Use one of your trained models from results dictionary
print("Using trained model for predictions:")

# Find the appropriate model from previous cells
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Option 1: Use the model.model (if your NetflixRatingModel wrapper contains a fitted model)
if 'model' in globals() and hasattr(model, 'model') and hasattr(model.model, 'predict'):
    trained_model = model.model
    print("Using model.model (RandomForest)")
# Option 2: Use results dictionary if available
elif 'results' in globals() and 'Random Forest' in results:
    trained_model = results['Random Forest']
    print("Using results['Random Forest']")
# Option 3: Train a new model if needed
else:
    print("No trained model found - training new Random Forest")
    from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
    from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
    
    # Train a simple RandomForest model
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
    trained_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, max_depth=10, random_state=42)
    trained_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Use the trained model for predictions
for desc in test_descriptions:
    result = predict_rating_from_description(desc, trained_model)
    print(f"\nDescription: {desc}")
    print(f"Predicted Rating: {result['predicted_rating']}")
    print(f"Confidence: {result['confidence']:.2f}")
    print("Top 3 possibilities:")
    for rating, prob in result['top_ratings'][:3]:
        print(f"  {rating}: {prob:.4f}")

# Simple deployment example for Netflix Rating Prediction
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import pickle
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Function to load the model (or train a new one if not found)
def load_or_train_model(model_path='netflix_rating_model.pkl', X=None, y=None):
    """Load a trained model from file or train a new one if not found"""
    try:
        # Try to load a saved model
        with open(model_path, 'rb') as f:
            model = pickle.load(f)
        print(f"Loaded model from {model_path}")
        return model
    except FileNotFoundError:
        print(f"Model file not found, training new model")
        # Train a new model if we have data
        if X is not None and y is not None:
            from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
            X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
            
            model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, max_depth=20, random_state=42)
            model.fit(X_train, y_train)
            
            # Save model for future use
            with open(model_path, 'wb') as f:
                pickle.dump(model, f)
            
            return model
        else:
            raise ValueError("Cannot train a new model - no data provided")

# Prediction function that works with trained scikit-learn models
def predict_rating(description, model, feature_columns, content_type='Movie', release_year=2022):
    """
    Predict content rating from a description
    
    Args:
        description (str): Content description
        model: Trained classifier model
        feature_columns (list): List of feature column names used by the model
        content_type (str): 'Movie' or 'TV Show'
        release_year (int): Year of release
        
    Returns:
        dict: Prediction results
    """
    # Clean text and extract features
    def clean_text(text):
        """Basic text cleaning"""
        import re
        if not isinstance(text, str):
            return ""
        text = text.lower()
        text = re.sub(r'[^\w\s]', ' ', text)
        text = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', text).strip()
        return text
    
    def tokenize_text(text, remove_stopwords=True):
        """Simple tokenization"""
        if not isinstance(text, str):
            return []
        tokens = text.lower().split()
        if remove_stopwords:
            # Simple stopwords list
            stopwords = {'a', 'an', 'the', 'and', 'but', 'if', 'or', 'because', 'as', 'of', 'at', 'by', 'for', 'with', 'to', 'from'}
            tokens = [word for word in tokens if word not in stopwords and len(word) > 2]
        return tokens
    
    def analyze_sentiment(text):
        """Simple sentiment analysis using word lists"""
        if not isinstance(text, str) or not text.strip():
            return {'polarity': 0.0, 'subjectivity': 0.0}
        
        # Simple sentiment lexicon
        positive_words = {'good', 'great', 'excellent', 'wonderful', 'fantastic', 'terrific', 'amazing', 'awesome', 'love', 'best', 'beautiful', 'happy'}
        negative_words = {'bad', 'terrible', 'awful', 'horrible', 'worst', 'poor', 'hate', 'disgusting', 'disappointing', 'boring', 'stupid', 'mess'}
        
        tokens = tokenize_text(text.lower())
        if not tokens:
            return {'polarity': 0.0, 'subjectivity': 0.0}
        
        # Count positive and negative words
        positive_count = sum(1 for token in tokens if token in positive_words)
        negative_count = sum(1 for token in tokens if token in negative_words)
        
        # Calculate polarity (-1 to 1) and subjectivity (0 to 1)
        denominator = max(len(tokens), 1)  # Avoid division by zero
        polarity = (positive_count - negative_count) / denominator
        subjectivity = (positive_count + negative_count) / denominator
        
        return {'polarity': polarity, 'subjectivity': subjectivity}
    
    # Clean text
    clean_desc = clean_text(description)
    
    # Create basic features
    features = {
        'type_encoded': 1 if content_type == 'TV Show' else 0,
        'release_year': release_year,
        'description_length': len(description),
        'title_length': 0,  # Not relevant for prediction
        'token_count': len(tokenize_text(clean_desc)),
    }
    
    # Add sentiment features
    sentiment = analyze_sentiment(description)
    features['sentiment_polarity'] = sentiment['polarity']
    features['sentiment_subjectivity'] = sentiment['subjectivity']
    
    # Create DataFrame with zero values for all expected features
    features_df = pd.DataFrame(0, index=[0], columns=feature_columns)
    
    # Update with actual values
    for feature, value in features.items():
        if feature in feature_columns:
            features_df.loc[0, feature] = value
    
    # Handle any genre features (setting all to 0)
    for col in feature_columns:
        if col.startswith('genre_') and col not in features:
            features_df[col] = 0
    
    # Make prediction
    predicted_rating = model.predict(features_df)[0]
    
    # Get probabilities
    probabilities = model.predict_proba(features_df)[0]
    
    # Sort probabilities
    top_ratings = [(model.classes_[i], probabilities[i]) 
                  for i in probabilities.argsort()[::-1]]
    
    return {
        'description': description,
        'predicted_rating': predicted_rating,
        'confidence': max(probabilities),
        'top_ratings': top_ratings
    }

# ---- Mock data and model for demonstration (if real model not available) ----
def create_mock_model_and_data():
    """Create mock model and data for demonstration"""
    # Mock feature columns
    feature_cols = [
        'type_encoded', 'release_year', 'description_length', 'title_length',
        'token_count', 'sentiment_polarity', 'sentiment_subjectivity',
        'genre_Dramas', 'genre_Comedies', 'genre_Action_&_Adventure'
    ]
    
    # Create a simple dataset with Netflix ratings
    ratings = ['TV-MA', 'TV-14', 'TV-PG', 'PG-13', 'R', 'PG', 'G', 'TV-Y', 'TV-Y7']
    mock_X = pd.DataFrame(np.random.rand(100, len(feature_cols)), columns=feature_cols)
    mock_y = pd.Series(np.random.choice(ratings, size=100))
    
    # Create and train a simple model
    model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=10, max_depth=5, random_state=42)
    model.fit(mock_X, mock_y)
    
    return model, feature_cols, mock_X, mock_y

# ---- Demo deployment ----
def run_prediction_demo():
    """Run a demonstration of the rating prediction system"""
    try:
        # Try to load an existing model and data
        model = load_or_train_model()
        # If we have a custom model in a variable named 'model' with attribute 'model'
        if hasattr(model, 'model'):
            model = model.model
        
        # Get feature columns
        if 'X' in globals():
            feature_columns = globals()['X'].columns.tolist()
        else:
            # Use a standard set if X not available
            feature_columns = [
                'type_encoded', 'release_year', 'description_length', 'title_length',
                'token_count', 'sentiment_polarity', 'sentiment_subjectivity'
            ]
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Using mock model for demonstration: {e}")
        model, feature_columns, _, _ = create_mock_model_and_data()
    
    # Example descriptions for prediction
    test_descriptions = [
        "A heartwarming story about friendship and growing up in a small town.",
        "A brutal examination of violence and revenge in the criminal underworld.",
        "A funny comedy about college students planning the ultimate party.",
        "An exploration of scientific discoveries that changed human history.",
        "A children's animated feature following magical creatures on a quest.",
        "A terrifying thriller where a family is stalked by supernatural entities."
    ]
    
    print("\n===== NETFLIX RATING PREDICTION SYSTEM =====\n")
    print("This system predicts content ratings based on descriptions\n")
    
    # Make predictions for each description
    results = []
    for i, desc in enumerate(test_descriptions):
        result = predict_rating(desc, model, feature_columns)
        results.append(result)
        
        print(f"\nExample {i+1}:")
        print(f"Description: {desc}")
        print(f"Predicted Rating: {result['predicted_rating']}")
        print(f"Confidence: {result['confidence']:.2f}")
        print("Top 3 possibilities:")
        for rating, prob in result['top_ratings'][:3]:
            print(f"  {rating}: {prob:.4f}")
    
    # Visualize predictions
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    
    # Plot confidence for each prediction
    confidences = [result['confidence'] for result in results]
    labels = [result['predicted_rating'] for result in results]
    colors = sns.color_palette("husl", len(set(labels)))
    color_map = {label: color for label, color in zip(set(labels), colors)}
    
    plt.bar(range(len(test_descriptions)), confidences, 
            color=[color_map[label] for label in labels])
    
    plt.xticks(range(len(test_descriptions)), 
               [f"Example {i+1}" for i in range(len(test_descriptions))], 
               rotation=45)
    plt.ylabel('Prediction Confidence')
    plt.title('Rating Prediction Confidence for Examples')
    
    # Add legend
    handles = [plt.Rectangle((0,0),1,1, color=color) for label, color in color_map.items()]
    plt.legend(handles, color_map.keys(), title="Ratings")
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    print("\nPrediction service demonstration completed.")

# Run the demonstration
if __name__ == "__main__":
    run_prediction_demo()

# Analysis of challenges and limitations in the Netflix Rating Prediction project
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, classification_report
from sklearn.model_selection import learning_curve
import pickle

def analyze_challenges():
    """Analyze and visualize challenges and limitations of the model"""
    print("\n===== CHALLENGES & LIMITATIONS ANALYSIS =====\n")
    
    # --- Load or create data for analysis ---
    try:
        # Try to load real data from variables
        if all(var in globals() for var in ['X', 'y', 'X_test', 'y_test']):
            print("Using existing dataset variables")
            features = globals()['X']
            labels = globals()['y']
            X_test = globals()['X_test']
            y_test = globals()['y_test']
            
            # Try to load actual predictions
            if 'model' in globals() and hasattr(globals()['model'], 'predict'):
                model = globals()['model']
                predictions = model.predict(X_test)
            else:
                predictions = None
        else:
            # Load from files if available
            df = pd.read_csv('netflix_titles.csv')
            raise NotImplementedError("Loading from file not implemented in this example")
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Creating mock data for demonstration: {e}")
        # Create mock data for visualization
        ratings = ['TV-MA', 'TV-14', 'TV-PG', 'PG-13', 'R', 'PG', 'G', 'TV-Y', 'TV-Y7']
        
        # Create imbalanced distribution similar to real Netflix data
        counts = [3200, 2100, 860, 490, 800, 290, 40, 310, 330]  # Similar to real distribution
        
        # Generate mock labels
        all_labels = []
        for rating, count in zip(ratings, counts):
            all_labels.extend([rating] * count)
        
        labels = pd.Series(all_labels)
        features = pd.DataFrame(np.random.rand(len(labels), 10))
        
        # Create mock test set and predictions
        from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
        _, X_test, _, y_test = train_test_split(features, labels, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
        
        # Create plausible predictions (mostly right, some wrong)
        predictions = []
        for true_label in y_test:
            if np.random.random() < 0.5:  # 50% accuracy
                predictions.append(true_label)
            else:
                # Misclassify to a similar rating
                other_ratings = [r for r in ratings if r != true_label]
                predictions.append(np.random.choice(other_ratings))
    
    # --- 1. Class Imbalance Analysis ---
    print("\n1. Class Imbalance Analysis")
    class_counts = labels.value_counts()
    class_percentages = class_counts / len(labels) * 100
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    ax = sns.barplot(x=class_counts.index, y=class_percentages.values)
    
    # Add percentage labels on bars
    for i, p in enumerate(ax.patches):
        height = p.get_height()
        ax.text(p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2., height + 0.5,
                f'{height:.1f}%', ha="center")
    
    plt.title('Class Distribution in Target Variable')
    plt.ylabel('Percentage of Dataset')
    plt.xlabel('Rating')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    print(f"Number of classes: {len(class_counts)}")
    print(f"Most common class: {class_counts.index[0]} ({class_percentages.values[0]:.1f}%)")
    print(f"Least common class: {class_counts.index[-1]} ({class_percentages.values[-1]:.1f}%)")
    print(f"Imbalance ratio (most:least common): {class_counts.values[0]/class_counts.values[-1]:.1f}:1")
    
    # --- 2. Performance Across Classes ---
    if predictions is not None:
        print("\n2. Model Performance Across Classes")
        
        # Confusion matrix
        cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, predictions)
        
        # Normalize by true labels (rows)
        cm_norm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        
        plt.figure(figsize=(14, 12))
        sns.heatmap(cm_norm, annot=True, fmt='.2f', cmap='Blues',
                    xticklabels=sorted(set(y_test)),
                    yticklabels=sorted(set(y_test)))
        plt.xlabel('Predicted')
        plt.ylabel('True')
        plt.title('Normalized Confusion Matrix')
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
        
        # Generate metrics by class
        report = classification_report(y_test, predictions, output_dict=True)
        report_df = pd.DataFrame(report).transpose()
        
        # Create correlation between class frequency and performance
        class_performance = []
        for cls in class_counts.index:
            if cls in report_df.index:
                class_performance.append({
                    'Rating': cls,
                    'Frequency (%)': class_percentages[cls],
                    'Precision': report_df.loc[cls, 'precision'],
                    'Recall': report_df.loc[cls, 'recall'],
                    'F1-score': report_df.loc[cls, 'f1-score'],
                    'Support': report_df.loc[cls, 'support']
                })
        
        perf_df = pd.DataFrame(class_performance)
        
        # Plot correlation between class frequency and performance
        plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
        plt.scatter(perf_df['Frequency (%)'], perf_df['F1-score'], alpha=0.7, s=100)
        
        # Add labels to points
        for i, row in perf_df.iterrows():
            plt.annotate(row['Rating'], 
                         (row['Frequency (%)'] + 0.5, row['F1-score'] + 0.02))
        
        # Add trendline
        z = np.polyfit(perf_df['Frequency (%)'], perf_df['F1-score'], 1)
        p = np.poly1d(z)
        plt.plot(sorted(perf_df['Frequency (%)']), 
                 p(sorted(perf_df['Frequency (%)'])), 
                 "r--", alpha=0.8)
        
        plt.title('Class Frequency vs. F1-score')
        plt.xlabel('Class Frequency (%)')
        plt.ylabel('F1-score')
        plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()
        
        corr = perf_df['Frequency (%)'].corr(perf_df['F1-score'])
        print(f"Correlation between class frequency and F1-score: {corr:.3f}")
        
        if corr > 0.3:
            print("> Strong class imbalance effect detected: Less frequent classes have lower performance")
        elif corr < -0.3:
            print("> Unusual pattern: Less frequent classes have better performance")
        else:
            print("> Weak correlation: Class frequency doesn't strongly impact performance")
    
    # --- 3. Feature Analysis ---
    print("\n3. Feature Importance Limitations")
    
    # Create or load feature importance
    try:
        if 'model' in globals() and hasattr(globals()['model'], 'feature_importances_'):
            model = globals()['model']
            feature_importance = pd.DataFrame({
                'Feature': features.columns,
                'Importance': model.feature_importances_
            }).sort_values('Importance', ascending=False)
        else:
            # Generate mock feature importance
            feature_importance = pd.DataFrame({
                'Feature': ['release_year', 'title_length', 'sentiment_polarity', 
                           'description_length', 'sentiment_subjectivity', 'token_count'] +
                           [f'genre_{i}' for i in range(4)],
                'Importance': [0.15, 0.12, 0.10, 0.09, 0.08, 0.07] + 
                              [0.05, 0.04, 0.03, 0.02]
            })
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Using mock feature importance: {e}")
        feature_importance = pd.DataFrame({
            'Feature': ['release_year', 'title_length', 'sentiment_polarity', 
                       'description_length', 'sentiment_subjectivity', 'token_count'] +
                       [f'genre_{i}' for i in range(4)],
            'Importance': [0.15, 0.12, 0.10, 0.09, 0.08, 0.07] + 
                          [0.05, 0.04, 0.03, 0.02]
        })
    
    # Visualize feature importance
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.barplot(x='Importance', y='Feature', data=feature_importance.head(10))
    plt.title('Top 10 Feature Importance')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    # Calculate importance concentration
    top_feature_importance = feature_importance.head(3)['Importance'].sum()
    print(f"Top 3 features account for {top_feature_importance:.1%} of total importance")
    
    if top_feature_importance > 0.5:
        print("> High feature concentration: Model relies heavily on a few features")
        print("> Limitation: Model may not be capturing subtle text patterns effectively")
    else:
        print("> Balanced feature importance: Model uses diverse information sources")
    
    # Missing features discussion
    print("\nPotential missing features that could improve performance:")
    print("1. Content visual elements (not captured in descriptions)")
    print("2. Audio/sound characteristics (violence, language)")
    print("3. Director/actor reputation and previous work ratings")
    print("4. Cultural context and release time period")
    print("5. Content duration (longer content may have more mature themes)")
    
    # --- 4. Textual Limitations ---
    print("\n4. Text Analysis Limitations")
    
    print("\nDescriptions with similar text patterns but different ratings:")
    examples = [
        {
            "description": "A family drama about a father reconnecting with his estranged children.",
            "similar_ratings": ["PG-13", "TV-14", "TV-PG"]
        },
        {
            "description": "A gritty crime thriller following detectives hunting a serial killer.",
            "similar_ratings": ["TV-MA", "R", "TV-14"]
        },
        {
            "description": "A coming-of-age story about teenagers navigating high school challenges.",
            "similar_ratings": ["TV-14", "PG-13", "TV-PG"]
        }
    ]
    
    for ex in examples:
        print(f"\n- Description: {ex['description']}")
        print(f"  Potential ratings: {', '.join(ex['similar_ratings'])}")
    
    print("\nWhy descriptions alone are insufficient:")
    print("1. Missing visual context (violence level, nudity, etc.)")
    print("2. Subjective interpretations of similar themes")
    print("3. Regional/cultural differences in rating standards")
    print("4. Rating evolution over time (standards change)")
    print("5. Subtle thematic elements not captured in brief descriptions")
    
    # --- 5. Summary of Limitations ---
    print("\n5. Summary of Model Limitations")
    print("\nKey limitations of the current approach:")
    print("1. Class imbalance affects model performance on less common ratings")
    print("2. Text descriptions lack important visual and audio context")
    print("3. Reliance on metadata features over content characteristics")
    print("4. Similar descriptions can have different ratings based on execution")
    print("5. Limited ability to capture changing rating standards over time")
    
    print("\nPossible improvements:")
    print("1. Use weighted training to address class imbalance")
    print("2. Incorporate more metadata (actors, directors, runtime)")
    print("3. Implement advanced NLP techniques (transformers, BERT)")
    print("4. Add content-based features beyond text descriptions")
    print("5. Develop separate models for different content types and eras")

# Run the analysis
if __name__ == "__main__":
    analyze_challenges()

2. Incorporate more metadata (actors, directors, runtime)
3. Implement advanced NLP techniques (transformers, BERT)
4. Add content-based features beyond text descriptions
5. Develop separate models for different content types and eras

Final Project Report

Netflix Content Rating Prediction: A Text Analytics Approach

Project Overview

This project applies text analytics and machine learning techniques to predict content ratings (TV-MA, PG-13, etc.) for Netflix shows and movies based on descriptions and metadata. The project demonstrates the application of natural language processing techniques to extract meaningful insights from textual data.

Dataset

The Netflix dataset contains 8,807 titles with features including:

  • Content metadata (type, title, director, cast, country, release year)
  • Content descriptions
  • Rating information (TV-MA, TV-14, TV-PG, R, PG-13, etc.)

Methodology

1. Data Processing & Feature Engineering

  • Text Preprocessing: Tokenization, cleaning, and normalization of descriptions
  • Feature Extraction: Basic metadata features (release year, content type)
  • Text Analytics Features: Description length, token count, sentiment metrics

2. Text Analytics Techniques Applied

  • Tokenization: Breaking descriptions into individual words
  • Part-of-Speech Tagging: Identifying word classes and patterns in descriptions
  • Topic Modeling: Using LDA to identify content themes
  • Sentiment Analysis: Measuring emotional tone in descriptions
  • Word Embeddings: Capturing semantic relationships with Word2Vec
  • N-gram Analysis: Identifying common word pairs and phrases

3. Model Development

  • Trained multiple machine learning models (Random Forest, Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes)
  • Implemented model comparison and evaluation
  • Explored various feature combinations to maximize predictive power

Key Findings

1. Model Performance

  • Random Forest model achieved 46.47% accuracy on the test set
  • Most influential features:
    1. Release year
    2. Title length
    3. Sentiment polarity
    4. Description length
    5. Sentiment subjectivity

2. Topic Analysis

We identified 5 distinctive content topics through LDA:

  • Topic 1: Entertainment/Drama (world, love, friends, comedy)
  • Topic 2: Documentaries (documentary, series, film, lives)
  • Topic 3: Coming-of-age (young, school, woman, friends)
  • Topic 4: Family content (family, young, old, home)
  • Topic 5: Character-driven (man, family, father, woman)

3. Linguistic Patterns by Rating

  • TV-MA content: More adult themes, slightly negative sentiment
  • G and TV-Y content: More positive sentiment, family-oriented terms
  • PG-13 content: Balanced between extremes
  • R-rated content: Higher incidence of negative sentiment words

4. Word Embedding Insights

Word vectors revealed semantic clusters around:

  • Family-oriented terminology
  • Action/adventure terminology
  • Documentary/educational terminology
  • Each cluster correlates with different rating distributions

5. Classification Challenges

  • Similar descriptions can receive different ratings based on execution
  • Substantial class imbalance (36% TV-MA, 24% TV-14)
  • Content ratings standards evolve over time (captured in release year importance)

Applications & Implications

Practical Applications

  1. Content Moderation: Assist streaming platforms in assigning appropriate ratings
  2. Content Creation: Guide creators in tailoring descriptions for target ratings
  3. Content Recommendation: Improve recommendation systems with predicted ratings
  4. Regional Adaptation: Help identify content requiring rating adjustments for international markets

Insights for Content Industry

  1. Rating Evolution: Clear evidence that rating standards change over time
  2. Description Patterns: Specific linguistic patterns correlate with content ratings
  3. Sentiment Influence: Emotional tone in descriptions correlates with rating categories

Limitations & Future Work

Current Limitations

  • Moderate accuracy (46.47%) reflects the complexity of the task
  • Text descriptions lack important visual/audio context
  • Class imbalance affects performance on less common ratings
  • Similar descriptions can have different ratings based on execution details

Future Improvements

  1. Implement weighted training to address class imbalance
  2. Incorporate more metadata (actors, directors, runtime)
  3. Explore transformer-based models (BERT) for enhanced text understanding
  4. Add content-based features beyond text descriptions
  5. Develop separate models for different content types and eras

Conclusion

This project demonstrates the effectiveness of text analytics in extracting meaningful patterns from content descriptions. While the model's accuracy is moderate, it provides valuable insights into the relationship between textual characteristics and content ratings. The findings have practical applications for content creators, streaming platforms, and recommendation systems.

  2. Dan Jurafsky and James H Martin, Speech & Language Processing, 3rd edition draft, Stanford University
